WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Hi everybody, I'm Ryszard Szymański, I'm a staff engineer at Appsilon and a large part of my work is developing applications.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:18.000
One day I was working on a new feature. I was adding a UI badge indicating the status of content that users were creating in the app.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
The status value was based on a complex mix of parameters.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
So, I used all of the best practices that I know.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I wrote my tests, I asked for code review, I verified my logic in a staging environment.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
I was ready to release the new feature to our end users.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
And this is what I saw in production.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
An error. And so did our users.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Turns out, production data had edge cases I did not anticipate.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Reality was messier than staging.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And that's the point. Production is full of variables we cannot always predict.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Now, imagine a different reality.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.000
One where we can see things go wrong before our users ever notice.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
During this talk, I'd like to share deployment strategies that help us get there.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Starting with blue-green deployments.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
So, usually, you host your app on some kind of a server.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
While your users access it through a client. For example, a browser in their laptops.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And the idea behind blue-green deployments is that we have two separate app instances.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
One called blue, and the other called green.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And in the beginning, your users access the app through the blue instance.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
When you're ready to release a new version, you deploy it to the green instance.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
You verify if everything's working as expected there.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And if it does, you switch the traffic.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
So now your users access the new version, but this time through the green instance.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
But that was the optimistic scenario where everything worked as expected.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
What if something goes wrong on the green instance?

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Well, in these cases, you find yourself in a much more comfortable situation.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Where you can calmly investigate what's wrong in the green instance.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:26.000
While your end users continue to use the stable version of your app on the blue instance.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Let's see how we can use this strategy on PositConnect.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So the way we can reverse traffic is by using vanity URLs.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
And I'll explain what those are in a bit.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And separate app instances can be achieved by having separate content items.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
So usually, when you deploy something on PositConnect, the URL would look sort of like this.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
So it's your connect URL slash content slash the GUID of your app.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
PositConnect allows you to configure a user-friendly URL called a vanity URL.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Where you can configure the exact path where your app is available.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:11.000
You can configure a vanity URL using the content settings in the PositConnect UI.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.000
And separate app instances can be achieved by having separate content items.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:23.000
So you can create two separate deployments on PositConnect and call one blue and the other green.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Let's see how an example blue-green deployment could look like on PositConnect.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So let's say our users are accessing the app through the my underscore URL vanity URL.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Which is initially configured for the blue content item.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Now we deploy the new version to the green content item.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And once we confirmed everything's working as expected, we reconfigure the same vanity URL.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.000
But this time for the green content item.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:01.000
You can automate this process using the connect API package in less than 40 lines of code.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Here's a QR code where you can find an example script.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Of course, you can perform this manually.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:16.000
But if you're looking for a fully automated script, I can imagine one where you can run a test suite.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
After you deploy the new version to the green content item.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:27.000
And after your tests pass, you would reconfigure the vanity URL and switch the traffic.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Now let's move on to feature flags.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So feature flags are also often called feature toggles or feature switches.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
They're essentially a mechanism for turning features on and off in your application.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
It's just a clever if statement.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.000
So a feature flag can be just this simple logical value.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And depending on whether it's true or false, we would enable or disable features.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:58.000
So in this case, if that feature flag is enabled, we would welcome the users to the new experience.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.000
But if it's disabled, we would welcome them back to the good and old experience.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
We can apply the same idea to applications.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:13.000
So let's say we have an app where we have two different tabs with two different features.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
We can hide one of the tabs behind the feature flag.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And this is how it could look like.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:27.000
So based on the feature flag value, we could insert a tab containing our feature or not.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Of course, there are other types of feature flags.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
These don't have to be simple logical values.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:45.000
But you can enable a feature for specific users or groups based on an environment variable or at a specific time.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Let's have a look at an example of how we can use Deposit Connect.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Let's get back to our example of an app with two different tabs with two different features.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And in the Deposit Connect UI, you can find the People tab where you can find information on users and groups.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And the reason I mention this is Deposit Connect provides you with information about the logged in user when accessing your app.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And that information includes their username and the groups to which they belong to.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And in case of Shiny, that information is available through the session parameter of the server function.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
Let's create a group called FeatureBGroup.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:40.000
And what we want to do here is to only show the FeatureB tab for the members of that group.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.000
So we can use the FeatureFlag package, which I have developed, which allows you to create a ConnectGroupFeatureFlag,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
where you specify the groups for which this flag should be enabled.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And here we'll specify the FeatureBGroup we just created.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:59.000
Now, in our code, we can check if that flag is enabled.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And if it is, we would insert the tab containing FeatureB.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:11.000
So what we just achieved here is a situation where different users accessing the same app might see a slightly different UI.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Members of the FeatureBGroup would see the FeatureB tab, while others who do not belong to that group would only see the FeatureA tab.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Imagine if we had applied this idea to the UI badges.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:33.000
What could have happened there is we could have hidden the UI badges behind the FeatureFlag that's only enabled for developers.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And that way, in production, only developers would see the error, while users would be able to continue using the app, but without the UI badges.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
But how do we deploy using FeatureFlags?

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
So in the beginning, let's say FeatureB is only accessible to the members of the FeatureBGroup.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:01.000
So everyone else does not have access to it.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:07.000
If we release it to everyone, we can change the FeatureFlag value to true.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And that way, we will enable this feature to everyone that's accessing our app.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
Let's have a look at another example.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:22.000
So the FeatureFlag package also allows you to create FeatureFlags that are connected to environment variables.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:28.000
So here we're creating one that's connected to the FeatureB environment variable.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:34.000
By default, if that environment variable is not configured, the flag will be disabled.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:41.000
But if we configure it and set it to true, it will now be enabled.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:50.000
We can combine that with the ability to configure environment variables in Deposit Connect UI and perform our deployments this way.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:56.000
So let's say in the beginning, our content doesn't have this environment variable configured.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
So FeatureB is not accessible to anyone.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:06.000
We can configure this environment variable and that way make FeatureB accessible to all of our users.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
So what's happening here is the deployment is not...

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
It does not mean we're deploying new source code,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:20.000
but we're just changing an environment variable value and releasing our new features that way.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:27.000
Okay, but what if we use blue-green deployments or FeatureFlags and their release still failed?

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:34.000
So while those strategies do help you minimize some risks, they're not silver bullets.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
So usually we have at least two options.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
One of them is to fix things forward.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:46.000
So the idea here is you see an issue, you fix it, you release a new version containing the fix.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:54.000
And that's useful in scenarios where the issue is small, does not disrupt users, and you exactly know how to fix it quickly.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
A good example of that is a typo in the UI.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
Or the other option is to roll back.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
And that means going back to a previous stable version of your app.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And that's useful in cases where the issue prevents your users from working in the app,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
and you really don't know what's going on and you need time to investigate.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.000
Thankfully, you can easily perform rollbacks in the PositConnect UI.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.000
So if you navigate in the top right corner to the source versions option,

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:33.000
you will be listed all of the bundle versions that have been used for this specific content item.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:39.000
And in there, you can pick a previous bundle and click the reactivate button,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.000
and that way bring back a previous version of your code.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
In the end, deployments don't have to be scary.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
By adopting the right strategies, like blue-green deployments or feature flags,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:59.000
and by knowing how to fix things forward or rollback quickly, we gain control.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Shipping to production should feel safe.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
And with the right approach, it can be.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
Thank you. That will be all from me.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
Here's my email, and you can also find me on LinkedIn.

